2. Classes for Finance Algorithms: \
\
(1) TimeValueOfMoney\
This class contains the methods to generate the user\'92s return objective, which is the minimum return required to realize the user\'92s desired retirement goal, based on the information user entered related to the goals. \
\
Present Value = Current Asset Holding entered by the user; \
Future Value = Desired Retirement Amount entered by the user; \
Annuity = Annual Income - annual expense entered by the user; \
Number of Years = Desired Retirement Age - User\'92s Current Age entered by the user;\
Internal Rate of Return (IRR) = Minimum Portfolio Return can achieve the user\'92s desired retirement goals.\
\
Method \'93calculateIRR\'94 gives the final IRR output and Method \'93analyzeReturnObjective\'94 tests whether the user\'92s investment objective is realistic. \
\
(2) RiskScore\
This class returns the user\'92s risk objective based on the survey taken by the user. \
Question 1 to Question 4 returns the risk score for the user\'92s willingness to tolerate risks. Question 5 and Question 6, together with the user\'92s investment time horizon, which was denoted as Question 7, determine the user\'92s ability to tolerate investment risks. All seven questions as a whole determine the user\'92s overall risk tolerance. \
\
Method \'93analyzeRisk\'94 interprets the risk preference behind the user\'92s risk score. \
\
(3) SuggestedAllocation (Note 1 and Note 4) \
This class returns the suggested asset allocation based on user\'92s risk objective. Please note that this allocation is not based on the user\'92s return objective. \
\
The algorithm is based on publications of several financial institutions, such as Charles Schwab and Wealthfront. \
\
(4) FinanceEquations  (Note 2, Note 3, and Note 4)\
This class contains the algorithm to return the Portfolio Return and Risk with the suggested asset allocation from the class Suggested Allocation. The portfolio return is weighted average return of each individual asset in the portfolio. The portfolio risk is measure by the portfolio standard risk. \
\
Please note the suggested portfolio return and risk may not be consistent with the user\'92s desired return and risk. However, the suggested portfolio return and risk are more realistic based on the analysis from the financial institutions. \
\
(5) FutureValueCalc\
This class contains the method to calculate the future portfolio value based on the current asset holding, annuity, investment horizon, etc. \
